[Category "Partnership Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "partnership_bidding/basic_major"]
[Student "S"]
{NORTH has a minimum 1\H opening bid - 13 points and five trumps.

SOUTH also has opening hand strength, 14 points for him. He also has four of NORTH's 
\Hs. He applies the "He who knows, goes" principle and 
bids 4\H.

IMPORTANT NOTE: Most experienced bridge pairs would not bid the hand quite this way, although they 
would arrive at the same contract. See some of the other BakerBridge lessons for more details.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "2"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "E:AJT874.AK5.AK3.9 63.97632.82.AKQ2 KQ92.QJ.Q764.J84 5.T84.JT95.T7653"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1S pass 3S pass 6S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 2, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "794dfb2793a4b0cb9f15d381cc42dae2b6e268d3a2c82fafd228e2d647f71ccb"]
[Category "Partnership Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "partnership_bidding/basic_major"]
[Student "S"]
{EAST has a powerful hand (21 points) with a good 6-card suit. He opens 1\S.

WEST has an 11-point Limit Raise with four trumps. She jumps to 3\S.

EAST now knows that the partnership holds at least 32 points, perhaps 33. Since he can see that 
the opponents have no way to win the first two tricks he decides to bid the slam, 6\S}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "S:A7652.76.A83.AJ4 K8.QT92.K754.T95 JT943.A53.9.K863 Q.KJ84.QJT62.Q72"]
[Declarer "S"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "S"]
1S pass 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: S, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:2, nBasis: 0, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "80891590179a7f78daae066ee93420887b832a06fb5f15bd6349aee79aa95969"]
[Category "Partnership Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "partnership_bidding/basic_major"]
[Student "S"]
{SOUTH has 14 points and opens 1\S, her 5-card Major.

NORTH could bid 3\S, a Limit Raise with his 11 points. But it is often a good idea, 
when you have five of the Major suit that partner opened with, to just go ahead and bid 
the game. So North should bid 4\S here.

See the NOTE in Deal 13. When you use weaker 5-card support hands for your jump to game, you 
need to find another way to describe your opening-hand-strength type hands.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "W:A87.T9863.A62.A8 Q52.74.QT74.JT54 94.AK52.KJ3.K962 KJT63.QJ.985.Q73"]
[Declarer "W"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
1H pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: W, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:3, nBasis: 2, nRot: 1, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "ce091be898ce64418528dcf1f0ee453153720d4dc4946499db07e18f05f2952c"]
[Category "Partnership Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "partnership_bidding/basic_major"]
[Student "S"]
{WEST has 13 points so he must open. He has five \Hs so he 
should open 1\H.

EAST, with 14 points and four \Hs knows there are 
enough points for a game contract and at least nine \Hs between 
the partners. She who KNOWS, GOES, so EAST bids 4\H.

This is similar to Deal 13.}

